[1]
Date: Fri, 20 Jan 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: NTV MSN NBC, Turkey [edited]
<http://www.ntvmsnbc.com/news/358116.asp>

Turkey's 1st wide-scale summit on measures to combat avian influenza is to
be held on Friday [20 Jan 2006] in Ankara. Health minister Akdag stressed
that the necessary short term measures were being taken but that the summit
would look at medium and long term plans.
Apart from having the governors of all of Turkey's 81 provinces, the summit
will also be attended by health minister Recep Akdag, the agriculture
minister, the forestry and environment minister, and the interior minister.
The governors from the provinces of Van and Igdir, where most of the human
cases of avian flu have occurred, will give briefings on the latest
measures being conducted and Edmond McLoughney of the United Nations will
also address the meeting.
All aspects of avian influenza, including human cases and bird migration
routes, will be discussed. To date, at least 5 people have died after
contracting the deadly H5N1 strain of the virus, with another 16 people
having been infected. 13 of Turkey's 81 provinces have confirmed outbreaks
of avian flu, with a further 28 reporting suspected outbreaks.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[A map demonstrating Turkey's confirmed and suspected HPAI outbreaks in
poultry, as of 17 Jan 2006, is available at
<http://www.ecdc.eu.int/images/maps/turkey_poultry_17jan06.BMP> - Mod.AS]
